<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Leave Japan Volcanic Island  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A few residents who remained on a Japanese volcanic
island plagued by eruptions and earthquakes left by boat Sunday,
the second day of a government-ordered evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 600 people left Miyake Island by ferry in the afternoon,
bound for Tokyo, about 120 miles to the north. The last ferry in
the three-day evacuation plan was scheduled to leave Monday, local
official Yoshiko Numata said.
</P>
<P>
   The order to leave came after 2,686-foot Mount Oyama erupted
Wednesday for the eighth time since early July. Only police, fire
and municipal personnel were expected to remain on the island after
everyone else was moved out.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of Miyake's population of 3,855 fled to the
mainland before Friday's evacuation order.
</P>
<P>
   The island, part of the Izu chain, has been blanketed with ash,
prompting warnings that heavy rain could set off mudslides. It has
also been shaken by thousands of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   The government set up shelters in Tokyo, which administers
Miyake, and dispatched ships to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say shifts in huge underground pools of magma are
responsible for the recent volcanic and seismic activity on Miyake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 0904 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Addresses Expellee Group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Tackling one of Germany's most sensitive political
topics, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder went Sunday before a group
representing millions of ethnic Germans expelled from eastern
Europe after World War II and told them he was sticking by his
refusal to push their claims for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The federal government will not encumber its relations with
these countries with political and legal questions that come from
the past,'' Schroeder told the Federation of Expellees at a
ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of the signing of the group's
charter. ''The former eastern territories belong to our cultural
inheritance, but not to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's president, lawmaker Erika Steinbach, did not
publicly express any disappointment over Schroeder's expected
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she emphasized that Schroeder was the first ''chancellor
of our Fatherland'' ever to address the group's annual ceremony and
said it was ''good for Germany'' that their chapter of history not
be ignored as embarrassing or shameful.
</P>
<P>
   Reprisals after Nazi Germany's defeat saw about 12 million
ethnic Germans dispossessed and driven from their homes in eastern
Europe. About 2 million were killed or died from starvation and
illness on the trek west or in detention camps.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder praised the signatories of the charter for their
rejection of violence and revenge and for distancing themselves
from extremists and neo-Nazis who dream of retaking once-German
lands to the east.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that work had begun at the German history museum
in Bonn on an ''important exhibition'' documenting the subject of
expulsions -- one of the group's minor demands.
</P>
<P>
   However, he skirted calls to push for inclusion of a right to
return for expellees in the charter of rights being drafted for the
European Union, arguing that all citizens will have freedom of
movement once those lands join the EU.
</P>
<P>
   Some expellees have argued that countries such as the Czech
Republic shouldn't be allowed to join the EU until they change laws
that legalized the confiscation of property from ethnic Germans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 0933 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Tours Russia Nuke Base  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Sunday
toured a nuclear submarine base on Russia's remote Kamchatka
Peninsula, getting a first-hand look at decommissioned vessels
Russia can't afford to dismantle alone.
</P>
<P>
   Russia doesn't have the equipment or the cash to clean up all
the nuclear reactors and waste left over from the Cold War. Of
particular concern to many Western countries are its dozens of
nuclear submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say they pose environmental dangers and are concerned
that the nuclear material inside could be sold illegally.
</P>
<P>
   In Kamchatka, the Russians asked Richardson for U.S. help
disposing of the material inside the decaying, rust-covered
submarines lined up in the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's visit to Kamchatka ended a tour across Russia this
week aimed at checking up on a program to make sure nuclear
materials are safely disposed of. On Friday, he unveiled two
storage facilities for spent nuclear fuel from submarines at the
Russian Pacific Fleet's main base.
</P>
<P>
   Although Richardson did not offer immediate help in Kamchatka,
he said the tour of the base showed how Cold War barriers had
fallen and Russia and the United States are working together to
prevent proliferation of nuclear goods.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seeing what we saw, which would have been unthinkable 10 years
ago, represents clear progress in our continuing, evolving
relationship,'' Richardson said. ''Clearly it has not been easy for
the Russians to have opened up their most secret of sites for us to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already provided several hundred million
dollars to help Russia build new nuclear waste storage and disposal
facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 0937 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Utility price hikes causes focus on little-known ISO  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Many of the fingers being pointed in the
wake of rising energy bills are aimed at a little-known entity that
serves as a sort of bazaar for the purchase of electricity in New
York state.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than three government agencies are making inquiries
into the Independent System Operator (ISO) and whether the spot
sale of power under its auspices this summer has unfairly
contributed to higher utility bills for some New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Service Commission, state Attorney General
Eliot Spitzer and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC)
are all looking into the Independent System Operator. FERC's review
is part of a national look at state and regional utility-pricing
organizations under utility deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   If the outright manipulation of prices has not occurred in the
sale of power through the ISO - as some critics have alleged -
Spitzer said officials must ask whether that entity is doing the
job it was designed to do.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO, based in the Albany suburb of Guilderland, is the
successor of the old New York Power Pool. That was a partnership
under which the state's utilities routed electricity to members at
times of peak demand from those who were generating more than they
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's deregulated utility landscape, the ISO was
created to serve in that same capacity and also to operate a sort
of daily auction for electricity purchases for utilities who need
to buy power. The hope was prices would be kept down by buying
electricity in a competitive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities in New York buy about half their power in long-term
contracts and the other half through purchases in the spot market.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO has attracted attention because of the wild fluctuations
in the prices utilities have been facing - $15 per megawatt hour in
low-demand hours to as much as $1,000 per megawatt hour during
peak-demand hours. In late July, the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission imposed a cap on ISO-sponsored spot purchases of $1,000
a megawatt hour until Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Some New York electricity ratepayers are seeing the increases
passed through in higher bills. Consolidated Edison's bills this
summer have been 30 percent higher than last summer, for instance,
despite the generally cool weather.
</P>
<P>
   But customers of New York State Gas &AMP; Electric, the Niagara
Mohawk Power Corp. and Rochester Gas &AMP; Electric have not seen
increases because those utilities are locked into no-pass-through
agreements on power charges with the state Public Service
Commission. NYSEG, in fact, has been running ads boasting that it
hasn't raised rates despite the volatility in energy markets.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO, despite being created after ''much thought and
examination by economists and policy wonks ... has not worked,
apparently,'' Spitzer told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need to examine why it has not worked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain has used ISO-like mechanisms in deregulating its
utilities industry, but has started to move away from them because
they aren't effective at controlling prices, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Service Commission is also reviewing the operation of
the ISO. But commission spokesman David Flanagan said the reasons
for energy price increases are probably far less sinister than
critics of utility deregulation have suggested: wholesale oil and
natural gas prices have about doubled in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the primary fuels used to run our generating
plants,'' Flanagan said. ''That is a big part of the equation. The
other big part is we have a very tight market in terms of supply
and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   When two Democratic state legislators declared utility
deregulation in New York a failure last week and called on Gov.
George Pataki to fire his Public Service Commission Chairwoman
Maureen Helmer, Pataki said the lawmakers should instead blame the
Democratic administration of President Clinton for global energy
price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is it is more expensive to produce electricity
today than it was a year ago for a range of reasons and that is why
the retail buyer is seeing some changes as well,'' said Tom
Garlock, a spokesman for the Independent System Operator.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, who is also a Democrat, said utility deregulation has
created ''too complex a structure'' to make any person responsible
for price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to blame any particular body or entity yet,'' he
said. But he added, ''There is no question that something is
seriously amiss.''
</P>
<P>
   ''All the indications are that the winter could see another very
serious price spike because of pressure on both the oil and gas
markets,'' he said. ''Whether anything can be done in the time
frame sufficient to address this winter's price squeeze remains to
be seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
