<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tactics and tone cloud distinctions in key House races  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Voters may have to do some homework this fall
in order to choose a candidate for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In three high-profile House races in New Jersey, candidates
share many positions and spend time arguing about who is more
committed to them. The focus is often about tactics or tone. There
have been debates over when and how to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Vying to succeed Republican Rep. Bob Franks in the 7th
Congressional District, Republican Mike Ferguson is running a radio
ad complaining about ''negative'' tactics employed by Democrat
Maryanne Connelly. Connelly questions Ferguson's commitment to some
positions they have in common.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly announced July 26 that she supports repealing a 1993
tax on Social Security benefits. The next day, Ferguson said he
supports the same idea.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Democratic candidates around the nation, Connelly is
calling for stronger gun-control laws. Unlike many Republicans,
Ferguson released a ''gun safety plan'' of his own that would
include mandatory trigger locks, criminal background checks on all
sales and licensing and registration of all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Sujata Tejwani, Connelly's campaign manager, said Ferguson is
''trying to blur the differences.'' Ferguson said voters should
appreciate his willingness to veer from his party's orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Dig a little and you find differences.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Ferguson proposes merit pay for good teachers and
an end to the tenure system. Connelly supports President Clinton's
proposal to use federal money to hire teachers and make classes
smaller. Ferguson supports, and Connelly opposes, allowing young
workers to divert a portion of Social Security taxes to private
savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th District, another priority race for both national
parties, Republican Dick Zimmer is challenging freshman Democratic
Rep. Rush Holt of Pennington. Zimmer, who formerly held the seat,
is running a low-key campaign that often seems to mirror Holt's
re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   Both men place environmental protection high on their lists.
Holt boasts the endorsement of the Sierra Club. But Zimmer notes on
his Web site that the Sierra Club has endorsed him ''each time he
has run for re-election'' - meaning his past elections, but not
this one.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the biggest controversy has been a tactical one.
Agreeing with complaints from the Zimmer camp, a cable station
pulled a Democratic Party ad that Zimmer said was inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer says that, had he been in Congress, he would have voted
to repeal the so-called ''marriage penalty'' in the federal tax
code. But Holt did in fact vote to repeal it. The Zimmer campaign
says Holt did so without enough gusto, evidenced by the fact that
he voted also for several Democratic alternatives that were
considerably less ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer campaign manager John Holub said Zimmer will draw more
direct distinctions as the campaign progresses. One will be on
permanent normalized trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Holt opposed the China trade measure, citing concerns over human
rights, worker conditions and treatment of the environment in
China. Zimmer says free trade is crucial to the high-tech
businesses in the 12th District, and that he would have supported
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent campaign swing through New Jersey, President Clinton
spoke at a fund-raiser for Holt and at one for Susan Bass Levin,
the mayor of Cherry Hill, whose challenge to Rep. Jim Saxton of
Mount Holly is another closely watched race.
</P>
<P>
   Levin paints Saxton as too conservative for New Jersey. But
Saxton has muted that argument by winning endorsements from the
Sierra Club; his 1996 Democratic opponent, John Leonardi; and the
former president of the New Jersey AFL-CIO, Charles Marciante.
</P>
<P>
   To draw a distinction, Levin hones in on Saxton's vote June 29
for a GOP plan to add prescription drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was almost entirely along party lines. Republicans said
their plan would help seniors at reasonable cost by subsidizing
their coverage through private insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats like Levin favor a more costly plan that would
guarantee the benefit to all 39 million senior citizens now
enrolled in Medicare. House Democrats called the GOP plan ''a
hoax'' designed to neutralize one of their issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
