<HEADLINE> Explosion in Pakistan Kills 3  </HEADLINE>
By MUNIR AHMED
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A bomb exploded at a crowded bus stop in
the eastern city of Lahore on Sunday, killing at least three people
and critically injuring 10 others, including children, police and
doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, triggered by a homemade remote-control bomb,
destroyed a bus and the bus stop's waiting room and shattered the
glass in nearby buildings, police said. It happened in the
afternoon in the outskirts of Lahore, the capital of the Punjab
province.
</P>
<P>
   No group has claimed responsibility for the explosion, which was
the third in the city this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The explosion caused a stampede,'' said Mohammed Arshad, a
police constable by telephone from a nearby police station. The
police cordoned off the area around the bus stop and removed the
victims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-year-old boy and a 6-year-old girl were among those
critically injured. Several other people had minor injuries,
doctors at a government hospital said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The blast threw me on the floor,'' said Sajjad Ali, 20, who
was injured on his head and shoulders. ''For a while I thought I
was dead. I couldn't see anything but smoke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khasta Khan, another victim, said he was having lunch when the
blast rocked the waiting room. ''I heard a deafening bang and then
my eyes opened in the hospital,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, there have been a series of bomb explosions in
major Pakistani cities, killing scores of people and injuring many
more.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani government routinely blames its neighbor India for
acts of sabotage, while India accuses Pakistan of fomenting
terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
