<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rebels Welcome Truce  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Separatist guerrillas in Indonesia's
Aceh province welcomed the extension of a cease-fire on Sunday and
called for new efforts to find a political solution.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and the rebel Free Aceh Movement agreed ''in
principle'' Saturday to continue the three-month truce, known
officially as a humanitarian pause, which was brokered June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are happy the humanitarian pause has been extended so that
the Acehnese people can carry out their daily lives in greater
safety,'' said Abu Tazurra, a senior rebel commander.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the extension has not been specified. However, a
joint statement obtained Sunday said representatives of both sides
would resume peace talks in mid-September in Geneva, Switzerland,
where the initial deal was struck.
</P>
<P>
   The truce has been marred by at least 68 killings. Each side has
blamed the other for the bloodshed while pledging to maintain
support for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deaths, the cease-fire has succeeded in stemming the
worst of the violence in the province, about 1,100 miles northwest
of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Tazurra stressed the new round of talks should concentrate on
establishing a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''There must be a political solution to the conflict and
international involvement by the United Nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid has promised to bring
peace to Aceh, which has seen more than 25 years of fighting
between government forces and rebels seeking an independent Islamic
state. At least 5,000 people have died.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has promised more autonomy and Islamic law for the
province, which is on the northernmost tip of Sumatra island and is
rich in oil and natural resources. But he has refused demands for
an independence ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
