<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Pols Cited on Immigrants  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The trial was swift and the sentence harsh: For
beating an African immigrant to death, a 24-year-old German was
jailed for life last week and his two teen-age accomplices
sentenced to nine years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The court's intention in the eastern city of Halle was to send a
stern message about neo-Nazi racism. But some argue that the
message should be directed equally forcefully at mainstream
politicians who speak unkindly about foreigners in their country.
</P>
<P>
   Their rhetoric, these critics say, is being taken by the
right-wing fringe as lending legitimacy to the violence that has
led to at least three deaths this year and dozens of other attacks,
including the one on 39-year-old Alberto Adriano, who died three
days after the three neo-Nazis beat and kicked him in a park on his
way home.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a catastrophe; is it any wonder that a small minority
would take these sayings and then begin to kill foreigners?'' said
Jean-Jerome Chico-Kaleu Muyemba, an immigrant from Congo, formerly
Zaire, who works with schoolchildren to combat prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and others say it's no coincidence that
attacks on foreigners have spiraled alongside increasingly strong
language from mainstream figures on sensitive issues such as
curbing immigration or dealing with the Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the statements:
</P>
<P>
   --''We need more people our country can use and fewer who take
advantage of our country.'' -- Bavarian Gov. Edmund Stoiber, head of
the Christian Social Union party, speaking in July.
</P>
<P>
   --''Kinder statt Inder'' (Children instead of Indians). --
campaign slogan intended to push education instead of bringing in
foreign high-tech workers, used by Juergen Ruettgers, deputy
chairman of the Christian Democratic party during his failed bid
last May for governor of Germany's most populous state in May.
</P>
<P>
   --''Germany's capacity for immigration has run over the limit.''
-- Interior Minister Otto Schily, a leading member of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democratic party, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim such statements encourage extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have the idea that they're doing something good for
Germany when they attack foreigners; 'We do what politicians want
to do but can't,''' said Juergen Micksch, head of the Intercultural
Council, a forum of churches, labor unions and human rights groups.
''They feel they are true patriots and these statements foster
precisely this atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   When Schily launched an initiative to combat right-wing
extremism in May, Micksch held his own news conference to criticize
Schily for his previous comments on curbing immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Stoiber, the Bavarian governor, is among those calling for a ban
on the extreme-right National Democratic Party. The NPD, for its
part, claims Stoiber has co-opted its own message about curbing
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   And although Ruettgers eventually distanced himself from the
''Children instead of Indians'' slogan under strong criticism, the
extreme-right Republikaner party adopted it for its own campaign in
North Rhine-Westphalia state.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan touched a theme always sensitive in Germany -- home to
7.3 million foreigners, about 9 percent of the population, but
still struggling with whether it views itself as a country of
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The Berliner Zeitung wrote in an editorial last month that the
''boat-is-full rhetoric'' of the main political parties has
''contributed to the acceptance of xenophobic thinking patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany is not alone in Europe in coming around to a
conservative view of immigration, regardless of the political
complexion the government of the day. However, it faces a tougher
quandary because of its past.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to make amends for the Nazi era, it has become one of the
most generous in accepting refugees from the Balkan wars and
asylum-seekers from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But compromises and cutbacks on immigration and asylum have been
numerous in recent years -- most contentiously during the debate
over relaxing Germany's outdated citizenship laws -- and continue
despite the stated liberal goals of the two-year-old Social
Democratic-led government.
</P>
<P>
   Even a liberal-sounding program to fortify Germany's flagging
high-tech industry with trained foreign workers contains caveats to
placate those wanting to keep immigration tight. Fewer permits are
being offered than industry wanted, and foreign workers are allowed
to stay for five years -- not long enough to qualify for
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Chico-Kaleu Muyemba, who became a German citizen in 1992, has
been to more than 1,000 classrooms as part of a program funded by
the education ministry of Brandenburg state, where he lives. The
aim is to acquaint young Germans with newcomers and prevent them
from becoming like the silent majority that stood aside as Hitler's
thugs propelled him to power.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers visit classrooms to answer any and all of the students'
questions -- sometimes things as trivial as how do dark-skinned
people blush.
</P>
<P>
   The point they seek to get across is that foreigners are an
integral part of German life. Take chocolate, for instance,
Chico-Kaleu Muyemba tells the students. The kids may think it's
something quintessentially German, but it's made from cocoa, which
comes from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you say 'Foreigners Out,' then you get no cocoa and can't
make chocolate anymore,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1255 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Body found of Marlton man swept away in Delaware River  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EWING, N.J. (AP) - The body of a Marlton man who was swept away
by swift currents in the Delaware River was recovered Sunday just
200 yards south of where he disappeared, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   State Police Sgt. Robert Singletary of the Wilburtha Barracks
said the body of Gilson V. Desouza, 24, was recovered by dive teams
just south of the Delaware-Raritan Canal about 11:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Desouza, a Brazilian national, is presumed to have drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said he disappeared about 2:20 p.m., a quarter mile
north of the Scudders Falls Bridge where he and five friends had
been swimming and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Desouza was wading in the river and went to an area that was
deeper - about 12 feet deep - when he was pulled under and away by
the current, which was stronger than normal because of recent
rains.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Saturday that one of the victim's companions
tried unsuccessfully to save him. That person was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   State police searched the river for about five hours Saturday,
using a helicopter, boats and divers, and resumed the search at 8
a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Desouza's companions described him as a weak
swimmer. He also was not wearing a lifejacket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
