<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jews Remember WWII Turkey Shipwreck  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Jews sang, cried and read poems in an
at-sea tribute Sunday to relatives who perished decades ago when
their ship -- loaded with Romanian refugees -- was torpedoed by a
Russian submarine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sleep in peace, my brother, sleep in peace all of you,'' said
Elena Kindler, whose brother was one of the 769 Jewish refugees who
boarded the Struma in 1941 to escape persecution from Romania's
pro-Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   Some 60 relatives were brought by boat to the location where
divers believe the Struma lies, more than 240 feet down on the
Black Sea bed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have a grave to mourn them,'' said Esthi David
Israel, who lost 13 relatives on the Struma. ''We are here to try
to connect to some spot in the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   After a prayer for the dead read by the deputy chief rabbi of
Istanbul, Nishak Haleva, and the sounding of the shofar, a ram's
horn used in religious services, Tamara Harari Margulies read a
poem she wrote to her sister upon arriving in Israel in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sea had its way. A scream in the heart of the ocean,'' she
said. ''No one to help or hear the agony of the helpless.''
Relatives from the United States, Israel and Britain threw flowers
in the sea and sang traditional Jewish songs.
</P>
<P>
   The overcrowded Struma set sail from the Romanian port of
Constanza in December 1941. Its motors quickly broke down, and
Turkish authorities tugged the boat to Istanbul's harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, neutral during the war, refused to let the refugees
disembark unless Britain granted them permission to enter what was
then Palestine. London refused.
</P>
<P>
   At one point a pregnant woman and two families were allowed off
the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Turkish authorities decided to tow the motorless boat
back out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Struma drifted for hours until a Russian submarine torpedoed
the boat on Feb. 23, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   The only survivor was 19-year-old David Stoliar, who hung on to
debris of the ship for 24 hours before being rescued by Turkish
sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Stoliar, who now lives in Bend, Ore., did not attend Sunday's
service but sent a letter which was read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ''For 58 years, no one asked anything about the Struma and it
seemed no one cared,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked Greg Buxton of Britain, whose grandfather perished on
the ship, for launching the diving expedition to try to find the
boat's wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Struma is found or not, many felt the ceremony gave
them finally a chance to be at peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a kind of closing of the circle,'' said Sonia Starosta
from Israel, who left Romania with her family on another ship in
1941. They were forced to leave her paternal grandfather behind
because of his diabetes problems. He later boarded the doomed
Struma.
</P>
<P>
   ''This releases things that were pent up inside for 60 years,''
said Amnan Waisman from Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Anschell, a historian specialized in Romanian Jewry, says
the Struma symbolizes the indifference of countries to the fate of
Europe's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only looking at the ship, you could understand that it was a
wreck. It could go nowhere, but hundreds of Jews were willing to
board that ship to save their lives,'' Anschell said. ''It is proof
of complete desperation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1329 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore has narrow lead in Gannett poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Al Gore has a narrow lead over George W.
Bush among New Jersey voters surveyed in the latest Gannett New
Jersey poll on the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Senate race is a statistical dead heat, according
to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential poll, Gore leads Bush 39 percent to 32
percent, with 25 percent were undecided. Five percent said they
would vote for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The poll finds Republican Bob Franks five points ahead of
Democrat Jon Corzine, but that matches the poll's margin of error -
plus or minus five percentage points. Thirty-nine percent of those
polled said they were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of 430 New Jersey voters who were
identified as likely to vote in November was taken Aug. 24-27.
</P>
<P>
   In a Gannett New Jersey poll released the weekend after the
Democratic National Convention, Gore led Bush by 10 points, 44
percent to 34 percent. A similar poll released immediately after
the Republican National Convention had Bush at nine points ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Gannett New Jersey poll Senate race numbers contrast with a
Quinnipiac University poll of registered voters taken Aug. 18-22.
The Quinnipiac poll found Corzine with an eight-point lead over his
Republican rival with 19 percent of voters undecided. That poll had
a margin of error of plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine spokesman Tom Shea told the Gannett State Bureau that he
doubted the Franks lead in light of the results of the other poll.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett poll director Gary Deckelnick suggested timing could
account for the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''A poll is a snapshot in time, and it reflects what people were
thinking at the time it was taken,'' Deckelnick said.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that both polls reflect a large number of
undecided voters. Methodology could also be a factor. While
Quinnipiac polled registered voters, Gannett's poll focused on
people identified as likely to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Franks campaign manager Charlie Smith said he thinks the latest
poll indicates voters are uneasy about Corzine's sweeping proposals
on education and health care reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are concerns about Jon Corzine's credibility and
an uneasiness about where and how he would pay for his proposals,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republican candidates led in northern New Jersey counties,
according to the Gannett poll, and Franks led 34 percent to 21
percent in central New Jersey. Democrats were stronger in southern
New Jersey. Gore led Bush 45 percent to 27 percent, while Corzine
led Franks 28 percent to 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll is sponsored by the seven Gannett daily newspapers in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Gannett New Jersey: http://www.injersey.com
</P>
<P>
   Franks for Senate: http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
<P>
   Corzine for Senate: http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-03-00 1333 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E.U. Keeps Sanctions on Serbia  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY ULBRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVIAN, France (AP) -- The European Union, though increasingly
skeptical about the effectiveness of economic and other sanctions
against Serbia, made no move to lift them Sunday for fear of
helping Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in this month's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   France, current president of the EU, is among the countries that
have been pushing for an end to the sanctions, imposed more than a
year ago during the war in Kosovo. The French and a number of other
EU nations believe the sanctions have failed to isolate Milosevic
and are alienating and hurting ordinary Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 EU foreign ministers, ending their weekend meeting at
this Lake Geneva resort, agreed that lifting the sanctions now
could help Milosevic win the election. The message the ministers
want to send, according to French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine,
is that a return to democracy in Yugoslavia would mean an end to
the European sanctions and a massive influx of aid.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia holds its presidential, parliamentary and local
elections Sept. 24 in a vote increasingly seen as a referendum on
Milosevic's rule. The Yugoslav strongman is facing his first
serious challenge after a decade in power from opposition candidate
Vojislav Kostunica, who leads all independent opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers here agreed ''that this was not the right time to
lift sanctions,'' British Foreign Minister Robin Cook said. ''That
would send a confusing message.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the EU nations see the sanctions as not particularly
effective against the government but serve only to anger and hurt
ordinary Serbs. But Britain, the Netherlands and Denmark, among
countries hesitant to ease the sanctions, see them as one of the
few weapons the EU can wield against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers, at their last meeting in July, already
began to ease the sanctions, agreeing to a temporary suspension on
a ban on commercial flights between Yugoslavia and the 15 EU
nations. They also added 50 firms to the list of 190 Serbian
companies exempted from EU financial sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the ministers, keen not to upset the fragile Middle
East peace process, skirted the question of a declaration of
statehood by the Palestinian leadership, settling for a pledge to
push both Israel and the Palestinians toward a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have said they would declare a state on Sept.
13, the target date they and the Israelis set for completing a
peace treaty. Most officials here believe Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat will postpone the declaration to give the negotiations a
little more time -- but they won't say so on the record.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said the EU's March 1999
statement acknowledging the inevitability of statehood for the
Palestinians speaks for itself. What is left to be sorted out, he
said, ''are the conditions to achieve that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
