<HEADLINE> Families on Film at Venice Festival  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy (AP) -- It's family film time on the Lido -- but not
in the usual sense. Think murderous moms. Doting, dotty dads.
Lesbian cheerleader daughters. From nasty to nice, from nuclear to
not, families are a hot topic at the Venice Film Festival's 57th
edition.
</P>
<P>
   One of the standout films so far, ''You Can Count On Me,'' by
first-time director Kenneth Lonergan, is the touching tale of a
brother and sister who were orphaned young and had only each other
to count on.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy, the straight-arrow sister, is played by Laura Linney, who
appeared in ''The Truman Show,'' ''Absolute Power,'' and ''Primal
Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced, she has an 8-year-old son and an uneventful life --
that is until her brother Terry, a likable screw-up played by Mark
Ruffalo, shows up after an absence of several years.
</P>
<P>
   ''You Can Count On Me,'' a co-winner of the Sundance Film
Festival's grand jury prize that boasts veteran director Martin
Scorsese as its executive producer, was screened out of competition
to excellent reviews.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the emotional scale is the family depicted
in the venerable French director Claude Chabrol's ''Nightcap''
(''Merci Pour Le Chocolat''). On the surface, everything seems
fine, but deep down inside Mom (played by Isabelle Huppert) is a
moral monster.
</P>
<P>
   Elegantly made, the film has a wonderful performance by the
always reliable Huppert, but the plot suffers from some gaping
holes, including one involving a drugged nightcap of hot chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Chabrol, 70, is a member of the jury this year and his movie was
screened out of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Huppert, a stalwart of French cinema, also appears in one of the
films competing for the Golden Lion: ''Comedy of Innocence''
(''Fils de Deux Meres ou Comedie de l'Innocence''), which director
Raul Ruiz calls a ghost movie ''without ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a strange and slow-moving tale of a boy who decides a
stranger, a woman whose own son has died, is actually his mother.
His real mother, played by Huppert, is drawn into a relationship
with the woman, seemingly hypnotized.
</P>
<P>
   Two other films among the 20 competing for a Golden Lion deal
with family life, Robert Altman's satirical comedy ''Dr. T and the
Women'' and ''Liam,'' by Britain's Stephen Frears, whose films
include ''Dangerous Liaisons'' (1988) and ''The Grifters'' (1990).
</P>
<P>
   ''Liam,'' the story of an Irish Catholic family in Liverpool in
the 1930s, premieres Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the wackiest film family at the festival is the
low-budget, Flemish-language comedy ''Everybody Famous!''
(''Iedereen Beroemd!'') by Belgium's Dominique Deruddere.
</P>
<P>
   It's a blackly funny story about how some people will do
anything to become famous. It centers on an out-of-work factory
hand, his plump daughter's show business aspirations and the
improbable way he gets her ''big break.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was screened out of competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1343 </TRAILER>
