<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State readies for school construction review  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The first emergency projects funded by New
Jersey's historic $8.6 billion school construction legislation are
expected to get under way this fall, state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The initial work will include fixing leaky roofs, repairing
faulty wiring and other safety-related repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some work on classroom expansion projects and construction of
new labs and libraries is expected to begin later this year, but
schools across the state will have to wait until at least next
summer for their biggest projects.
</P>
<P>
   State officials still are gearing up a massive bureaucracy to
review, approve and manage projects designed to comply with the
court-ordered construction binge.
</P>
<P>
   A critic said he fears the state is not preparing adequately or
quickly enough, leaving the state's 30 so-called ''special needs''
districts in the dark and without the necessary dollars to do the
job right.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman signed the legislation to begin the
state's largest public works project on July 18, complying with a
state Supreme Court ruling ordering replacement or repair of
crumbling buildings in the poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   About $6 billion of the funds are reserved for the special needs
schools, the remainder for richer suburban districts around the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our expectation is every district with a building will be
looking to take advantage of this program,'' said Dave Mortimer,
assistant commissioner in the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The exact amount of the first year's allotment of funding is not
known. State officials must first approve, then calculate, the
total value of two types of projects: fast-track jobs that address
emergency needs in poor schools and non-emergency projects in all
schools that are ready to go and are approved by the state.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mortimer, emergency repairs at all the 450 school
buildings in the poor districts are being assessed. He said about
125 of the reviews are nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Once approved by the education officials, these projects will be
forwarded to the Economic Development Authority, which will
estimate their costs, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The same procedure will be followed for any district that is
granted a waiver from a lengthier review process because it has
documented a need for a project that is ready to go. Twenty-five
districts have sought waivers. Nine have been approved already by
the Department of Education but have not yet received EDA
estimates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mortimer, ground could be broken for more than $600
million worth of construction by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Department of Education staff will review the
lengthier five-year plans of districts whose projects are planned
for future years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They include long-range plans for each of the special needs
districts. To date, nine are in the final stages of study, Mortimer
said. He expects to begin approving the special needs plans this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But David Sciarra, director of the Education Law Center which
sued the state on behalf of the poor school children, is not
confident the state will cooperate fully with the court order.
</P>
<P>
   Too few of the poor schools have received satisfactory early
answers from the state about their facilities plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's still an opportunity for the process to go forward
that respects the court order. We still have time to correct
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I would say that the Department of Education has yet to
demonstrate that it's up to this task,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sciarra's fears are realized, the Education Law Center will
again take the state to court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The final outcome of this, if the Department of Education does
not confront its shortcomings, is more disputes that wind up in
court and more delays for children to receive what they need and
what they are entitled to,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
