<HEADLINE> Borscht Belt comics and hotels mainly gone, but beet soup still reigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELLENVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - The Catskills now has a contest to
celebrate the food that accompanied the comics and hotels that
attracted Jewish crowds here for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural Borscht Belt Cookoff was held Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The award for the best beet soup went to Micky Lanza, who cooks
in a cafe she and her mother own in nearby Wurtsboro. Lanza, whose
kitchen career began just four years ago, after the Borscht Belt
had all but withered completely, borrowed from several cookbooks
for her prize-winning potage.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place soup was a thick variety made with beets,
onions, celery, fresh garlic and basil. Lanza added horseradish to
the traditional sour cream topping.
</P>
<P>
   ''She must have made three or four pots,'' said Lanza's mother,
Patricia. ''I ate till borscht was running out of my ears, till she
got one that was just it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why mother, not daughter took home the first prize - a
borscht belt, adorned with a soup tureen and the gently rolling
Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Borscht is still a mainstay of local hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ''People love it,'' said Harriet Brahms, vice president at
Kutsher's Country Club in Monticello, one of the last of the great
Catskills resorts. ''When people get here, they want to eat it.
They don't get it at home. It's a classic, and we make it very
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
