<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funding is biggest challenge for Connecticut's charter schools  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   As Connecticut's experiment with charter schools
enters its
fourth school year, it's not student achievement that's the biggest
challenge to the founders of the schools.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's money.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one's ready to throw in the towel yet,'' said John
Champion, who helped start Common Ground Charter High School in New
Haven three years ago. ''But it's becoming more difficult to make
significant gains year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   Champion, an experienced fund-raiser, didn't realize getting
grants for the school would be so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the foundations feel the state's trying to get away on
the cheap,'' Champion said. ''That the services we use the grant
for should be provided by the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools were created to spark creativity and free
educators of bureaucratic red tape by releasing them from local
school board control. They also are designed to create public
school choice.
</P>
<P>
   The state now has 16 charter schools, serving 2,139 students as
of last year. This year, the state will pay charter schools $7,000
per student.
</P>
<P>
   A report released this summer by the Evaluation Center of
Western Michigan University suggests there is no shortage of
paperwork at charters and that they actually cost 11 to 33 percent
more to run than regular schools. They get about $1,000 less per
pupil than other public schools in public aid.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Center for Education Reform in Washington, D.C.
found underfunding to be the norm among most of the nearly 2,000
charter schools across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the first charter law was passed in 1991, charter
operators have struggled against tremendous financial odds to
create a place where children can succeed and thrive
academically,'' said Jeanne Allen, president of CER.
</P>
<P>
   Many states recognize the funding inequity and are looking at
amending their charter laws, Allen said. Whether Connecticut will
depends on the new biennium budget to be hammered out this
legislative session by Gov. John G. Rowland and the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thomas Gaffey, a Meriden Democrat who is co-chairman of the
legislature's Education Committee, said that while charter schools
seem to be doing a good job, he is concerned with balancing their
needs against others, including the state's $1 billion commitment
to school construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland spokesman Chris Cooper said Friday the governor still
supports charter schools but could not say what would be proposed
for them in the new budget.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Education is looking into helping
charters secure facilities more easily, said Thomas Murphy, a
department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''But at the same time these are the same people who said, 'We
can do it better for less,' '' Murphy said. ''Maybe it can't be
done better for less.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dutton of Bridge Academy Charter School in Bridgeport said
the state was clear about how much they were giving charter schools
from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I had hoped that there would be more of a cost of living
built in automatically,'' Dutton said. ''They're asking us to do so
much - to revolutionize education. It doesn't make sense to fund us
at a lower amount.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
