<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Holds Parliamentary Election  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Billionaire businessman Rafik Hariri and
the candidates he supports were expected to make a strong showing
in Sunday's final round of parliamentary elections, a success that
could set up a clash with the Lebanese president.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri, a former prime minister who tried to rebuild Lebanon
following its devastating civil war, hopes to once again lead the
country, where political fortunes depend heavily on the desires of
neighboring Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates backed by Hariri made a strong showing in the first
stage of voting a week before and were expected to do well again
Sunday, in which residents of the former Israeli-occupied zone in
the south voted for the first time in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   If Hariri wins and goes on to seek the premiership, it could
create a confrontation with President Emile Lahoud, who names the
prime minister after polling parliament members. The second-round
election results were expected Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud backs current Prime Minister Salim Hoss and vehemently
opposes Hariri. Hariri and Hoss ran for separate Beirut seats; both
were expected to win their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri was accused during the campaign of using his vast fortune
to woo voters -- he says he merely has provided money for
scholarships as well as financial and medical aid to needy
Lebanese. He also was accused of shackling Lebanon with $20 billion
in debt during his 1992-98 government, when he launched a
multibillion dollar plan to rebuild Lebanon from the 1975-90 civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   Christians and Muslims, leftists and rightists teamed up with
Hariri in the campaign to protest the military's role in politics
and Lahoud's failure to right the economy. While the concerted
attack on Lahoud was unusual, at least one sacred cow remained: Few
candidates from either side criticized Syria's involvement. Syria
has 30,000 troops in Lebanon and dominates it militarily and
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri and Lahoud were both considered close to Syria and both
will be looking for its support.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows how a prime minister is made in Lebanon -- this
will be decided by the head of state in coordination with
Damascus,'' Interior Minister Michel Murr, a Lahoud ally, said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, Syrian President Bashar Assad has met Lebanese
candidates from all factions, including Hariri and Hoss, in what is
viewed as preparation for determining who will be the next prime
minister and an attempt to keep the Hariri-Lahoud rivalry from
creating dangerous divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Some 259 candidates contested 65 seats in the legislature Sunday
following voting for the 63 other seats a week earlier in North and
Mount Lebanon provinces.
</P>
<P>
   The second round of voting, which took place in Beirut, the
eastern Bekaa Valley and the southern provinces, was largely
peaceful. Two men were stabbed by supporters of opposing candidates
in Beirut; security forces also picked up a campaign official for
allegedly bribing voters.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 million out of 1.4 million eligible voters were
registered to cast ballots Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In south Lebanon, Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri's pro-Syrian
Amal group teamed up with Shiite Muslim rivals of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah against traditional Shiite Muslim
politicians and a former Hezbollah chief who is fielding
candidates. Hezbollah Secretary-General Sheik Hassan Nasrallah
issued a religious ruling Sunday ordering followers to vote for the
Amal-Hezbollah ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah and Amal led a guerrilla war against Israeli forces in
southern Lebanon and hoped to bank on increased popularity after
Israeli troops withdrew from the border zone in May, ending an
18-year occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that residents of the former Israeli-occupied zone
in the south voted was in the 1972 parliamentary elections. There
were no elections in Lebanon during the civil war and parliamentary
polls in 1992 and 1996 did not include the border areas because of
the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very proud about the election,'' said Munah Samara in
Marjayoun after voting for the first time since 1972. The town is
the former stronghold of Israeli-backed militiamen, about five
miles north of the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the liberation, the elections mean the return of
legitimate authority and a move for the better in a region that has
been neglected for long,'' added the 50-year-old businessman who
voted for opponents of the Amal-Hezbollah ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in Muslim areas of the southern border zone was heavier
than in Christian areas, like Marjayoun, where Eastern Orthodox
Bishop Elias Kfoury said Christian turnout was low ''because some
people are either in prison or outside the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the 6,000 Lebanese who fled to Israel in the final
hours of the occupation were Christians allied with the Jewish
state. Other residents are in jail for collaborating with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Only 500 out of 8,000 eligible voters in Marjayoun were expected
to vote, said Moussa Jibran, the town's Moukhtar, or elder.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, voting in Shiite areas was brisk and residents
appeared to back the guerrillas. ''They gave their blood for the
liberation of the country and they have my vote,'' said Mahmoud
Beydoun, a 55-year-old butcher in Bint Jbeil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1443 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran: US Attempts to Lift Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's parliament speaker said Sunday that
attempts are being made in the United States to lift trade
sanctions against Iran, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported after American and Iranian lawmakers met for the first
time since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems that there are efforts under way in the United States
for lifting sanctions against Iran,'' IRNA quoted Mahdi Karrubi as
saying Sunday after returning from New York where he and four other
Iranian lawmakers attended a meeting of world parliament leaders at
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Karrubi did not provide details, but IRNA said Karrubi also met
representatives of some American companies who want the U.S.
sanctions lifted. The speaker told state-run Tehran television
Sunday that he met leaders of American oil companies and discussed
the sanctions issue with them.
</P>
<P>
   American companies are barred under the 1996 sanctions law from
investing more than $20 million in Iran's oil and gas sector. As a
result, U.S. firms have lost billions of dollars in contracts to
European competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, a Republican from Pennsylvania, Rep. Robert
Ney, an Ohio Republican who favors increased dialogue with Tehran,
and two other lawmakers, Eliot Engel and Gary Ackerman, both
Democrats from New York, met Karrubi and four other Iranian
lawmakers at a Metropolitan Museum of Art reception sponsored by
the American Iranian Council, which seeks improved relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-reform Hayat-e-Now daily newspaper quoted Karrubi as
criticizing ''hostile policies'' pursued by the U.S. government and
Congress against Iran and as saying the meeting had ''not been
planned.'' He acknowledged, however, that at the museum the
lawmakers discussed ''closer relations'' between Tehran and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said Thursday that the meeting was ''one step removed''
from official government-to-government contacts, which were severed
after the seizure of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a State Department spokesman said Sunday there
has been no change in the sanctions policy toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Tehran University professor and political analyst Davoud
Hermidas Bavand described the meeting as a step in accordance with
the national interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Hayat-e-Now quoted Karrubi as saying 10 U.S. senators signed a
letter to Iran's reformist-dominated parliament seeking meetings in
Iran, the United States or a third country. The letter was written
after the reformist-dominated parliament, or Majlis, was formed in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lifted trade sanctions in March relating to certain
Iranian luxury goods, including caviar, carpets and pistachios,
after reformists won February legislative elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
