<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Prisoners Escape in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By MERITA DHIMGJOKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO-led peacekeepers and
U.N. police using dogs scoured northern Kosovo on Sunday to track
down Serb prisoners who escaped from a detention center after
overpowering the guards.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen Kosovo Serbs, some of them facing charges of genocide
and crimes against humanity, fled from a U.N. facility in the
primarily Serb part of the divided city of Kosovska Mitrovica on
Saturday evening, said Susan Manuel, a U.N. spokeswoman. Two were
caught quickly, but the rest remained at large.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of NATO-led peacekeepers and U.N. police used dogs to
track the men through a wooded area near the jail. Troops threw up
roadblocks leading to Serbia proper, as the Serb escapees would be
unlikely to retreat toward the southern, predominantly ethnic
Albanian part of Kosovska Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel called the incident ''extremely serious'' and said it
would damage the reputation of NATO-led peacekeepers and the United
Nations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very bad signal for the rest of the people in
Kosovo, who had depended on us to bring people to justice from the
war of last year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' top representative in Kosovo, Bernard
Kouchner, expressed anger and frustration with the ease in which
the men slipped away and ordered an immediate review of the
province's detention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The men had been held since NATO-led troops took over the
southern Serb province last year and have been waiting for trial as
U.N. officials struggled to organize a justice system.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and NATO peacekeepers have controlled Kosovo
since June 1999, after the end of a 78-day air war that forced
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end his crackdown on
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The escape took place at 8:45 p.m. when a U.N. policeman was
taking a prisoner back to his cell after the man had made a phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   The other detainees in the cell overpowered the policeman, beat
him and threatened him with a gun that had been smuggled into the
prison, a U.N. statement said. They snatched his keys and freed
other detainees from other cells.
</P>
<P>
   The escapees threatened the remaining guards with the gun, bound
them, and locked them inside a cell before fleeing. The officers
alerted troops after freeing themselves 90 minutes later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1456 </TRAILER>
