<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For release 12:01 a.m. Monday, Sept. 4, &AMP; thereafter  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW WELSH-HUGGINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) - Being turned off by a candidate can make
for more than heated lunch table talk. A new Ohio State University
study suggests that people are more likely to vote in a
presidential election if they strongly dislike one of the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''In lots of areas of life people are much more motivated by the
threat of a loss than they are by the opportunity of a gain,'' said
Jon Krosnick, a professor of psychology and political science.
''The minute you've got a candidate you don't like, the possibility
of them winning is a threat and that motivates you to get out of
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Krosnick and colleagues from Princeton, Northwestern University
and the University of Chicago studied data from U.S. presidential
elections collected from 1972 to 1988 by the National Election
Study.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys included face-to-face interviews with more than
5,000 voters. The National Election Study checked names at local
election boards to verify whether individuals voted.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis of voter turnout was part of a larger study that
applied psychological theory to voter decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw support for a set of principles that we then carried
into a world of politics,'' Krosnick said. ''Is it possible people
evaluate candidates the way they evaluate breakfast cereals and
potential vacation spots? The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was presented at the American Psychological
Association's annual meeting earlier this summer and at the
American Political Science Association's annual conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's other findings:
</P>
<P>
   - First impressions count strongly in how voters decide on a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   - Despite a perceived cynicism about politics, people hold out
optimism for potential new candidates.
</P>
<P>
   - Negative information has more impact on voters than positive.
</P>
<P>
   - Less knowledgeable voters make decisions about candidates in
the same way informed voters do.
</P>
<P>
   ''In contrast to the simple-minded presumption that people walk
into the voting booth and make a decision at that point, people are
forming impressions about a candidate all along during the
campaign,'' Krosnick said. ''Their impressions are driven more by
what people learned early about a candidate rather than what they
learned last-minute.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of social psychological literature that indicates
that first impressions do count, ''and there's some supporting
evidence for that applied to politics,'' said William Berkowitz, a
psychology professor at the University of Massachusetts, Lowell
campus, who was not a member of the Ohio State study.
</P>
<P>
   Krosnick said there is nothing irresponsible about applying
everyday decision-making processes to electing a president.
</P>
<P>
   ''It simply shows how universal these principles of human
judgment are,'' he said. ''You don't have to be involved deeply in
the political domain to use a sophisticated style of reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   End advance for release 12:01 a.m. Monday &AMP; thereafter
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
