<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension mounts between condo owners and their associations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A growing number of residents of condo
villages and town house developments in New Jersey have begun to
complain that the volunteer homeowners associations that run their
neighborhoods are operating beyond democratic control.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Connolly, the director of codes and standards for the state
Department of Community Affairs, said he now takes more complaints
about homeowners associations than landlords.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing what goes on in some of these little
governments,'' Connolly told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Sunday's
editions. ''These associations carry out many of the functions of
government. They're little democracies. The idea is to make more
workable democracies out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the ''covenants'' of the associations carry as
much power as their township council.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the associations strictly regulate fence heights,
door colors, signs, flags. In some cases, banned items include
television antennas, pickup trucks and outdoor clotheslines.
</P>
<P>
   Those who break the rules face fines and, if they refuse to pay,
liens.
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey law, the associations are treated as nonprofit
corporations, rather than governmental bodies. Their leaders are
elected by residents and unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   The associations formed as a way to pass and maintain strict
rules that protect property values, and leaders say they are
reasonable in their requests and enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the associations say the lack of regulation allows
the associations to enact arbitrary rules without any kind of
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ''People feel they've been cut out of the democratic process,''
said Stan Maron, a resident of Galaxy Towers in Guttenberg. ''The
constitutional rights that apply to people living in a city don't
apply once they buy into a homeowners association.''
</P>
<P>
   Maron is president of the Common-Interest Homeowners Coalition,
a group of residents pushing reforms currently under consideration
by state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Community Affairs also is supporting reforms
designed to make the associations more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 New Jersey residents live in association-run
complexes, some as large as small towns.
</P>
<P>
   An uproar came in a golf-course retirement community in
Middlesex County, called Clearbrook, when the association decided
to spend $3.7 million of residents' dues on a clubhouse project -
without their approval.
</P>
<P>
   After some sued and won, a bylaw was written to require
referendums on large expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed legislation would require associations to have
independent panels handle disputes, and would name the Department
of Community Affairs as the final arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also requires associations to hold elections using
secret ballots, which would be counted by someone outside the
organization. They also would have to open financial records and
take bids for large contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Associations are watching the proposed reforms with some
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're dealing with all volunteers. It's pretty much a
thankless job, and basically, somebody has to do it,'' said Phyllis
Matthey, who runs a group of association leaders called the
Coalition of Associations for Political Action. ''If you get to
heavy-handed, people will resign and the places will fall apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-03-00 1537 </TRAILER>
