<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Transit shortfall raises doubts about future rail projects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey Transit's recent disclosure of a
possible $2.2 billion funding shortfall over the next five years is
raising doubts about the prospects for several major rail projects.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are a passenger line linking Monmouth, Ocean and
Middlesex counties, a rail extension to Phillipsburg in Warren
County, a Gloucester County light rail line and a light rail system
serving Elizabeth in Union County.
</P>
<P>
   All have been pitched to the transit agency by county officials
and passenger rail advocates, but none has been funded.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics fear the agency's financial situation may force it to
focus exclusively on maintaining existing service and financing
projects already under way.
</P>
<P>
   ''The long-range projects are interesting - they are important -
but they would have problems if they diverted money from their core
programs in order to pay for the long-range things,'' Martin
Robins, director of Rutgers University's Transportation Policy
Institute, told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit leaders say money will be found for essential
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''I happen to believe that necessity is the mother of
invention,'' said Executive Director Jeffrey Warsh.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's report warning of a revenue shortfall is based on
no increase in federal and state funding and no fare increase. More
funding in any of those areas could help produce money for new
projects, officials say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
