<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Protest Fuel Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French truck drivers and farmers on Sunday were
preparing to block fuel refineries and storage areas nationwide,
the latest development in a national wave of protests over rising
fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Transport Ministry said negotiations with truck drivers'
unions were ongoing, but truckers said they had suspended the talks
this weekend to ready for the blockades, expected to start
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have fundamentally, totally and exclusively dedicated
ourselves to organizing the protest,'' Jean-Paul Deneuville, a
representative of the National Federation of Truck Drivers, told
France-Info radio.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters planned to target sites nationwide, from Bayonne near
the Spanish border to Dunkirk in the north to Strasbourg in the
eastern Alsace region.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, French fishermen blocked ports and staged
demonstrations until they reached an agreement with the Agriculture
Ministry on Thursday to help offset their fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, truck drivers and taxi drivers added their voices to
the protests over the soaring French fuel prices, which have risen
on the back of skyrocketing crude prices.
</P>
<P>
   French truckers say the cost of diesel fuel has risen 40 percent
in the past year to about $2.55 per gallon, compared to a current
average of $1.58 francs per gallon in the United States. After
Britain, France has the highest fuel taxes in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fishermen, farmers and taxi drivers, truck drivers
receive little compensation for fuel taxes. They say fuel costs
them 7 percent of their revenues, when it should amount to only 2
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
