<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece PM: Economy Is on Right Track  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   THESSALONIKI, Greece (AP) -- In an effort to separate the
prospects of the Greek economy from the stock market's recent
tumble, Premier Costas Simitis said Sunday that the stock
exchange's ups and downs aren't indicative of the economy's course.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stock market is a market and the government shouldn't
intervene in a market.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference at the International Trade Fair
in Thessaloniki, the Greek premier said, however, that more
transparency in the investment programs of the listed companies is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''My firm belief is that companies should make public their
investment plans,'' Simitis said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has faced criticism that it hasn't enacted
legislation that would monitor the way profits from share capital
increases or initial public offerings are used.
</P>
<P>
   Simitis expressed confidence that the stock market's long-term
course will be positive, but said participants should be careful
with their investment choices.
</P>
<P>
   The general share index in Athens has lost more than 40 percent
of its value since its all-time high of 6355 points on Sept. 17,
1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
