<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio rejects complaints that he's not campaigning hard enough  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -Shrugging off reported complaints by Republican
leaders that he's not campaigning hard enough, GOP Senate candidate
Rick Lazio said Sunday he is ''very comfortable with where we are
in key parts of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, mingling with bathers and lunchgoers at a beach club in
Rockaway, Queens, said people should remember that he entered the
race only three months ago, after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew,
and that he still must devote some time to his role as a member of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those handicaps, Lazio said he was confident that voters
would prefer him over the Democratic contender, first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is very apparent that as long as I communicate my
mainstream record, we will win this race,'' he said. ''My opponent
cannot say anything positive about New York. She cannot cite
anything she's ever done for the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that left Mrs. Clinton with ''no option other than to
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said Lazio ''entered this race
by attacking Mrs. Clinton, and just put up one of the most negative
ads of the cycle this past week. We will continue to talk about our
positive message.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported Sunday that unidentified Republican
party strategists were ''frustrated'' by the ''passive'' pace of
Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Several Lazio supporters at the beach club agreed that his
campaign has been a bit on the lazy side. ''I think he needs to do
a little more,'' said Helen Muchewicz.
</P>
<P>
   ''She (Clinton) is working hard. He's got to get out there a
little more,'' agreed Muchewicz's son in law, Frank Keating.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was warmly received at the Breezy Point Surf Club, whose
5,000 members are mostly middle class, many of them retired civil
servants, and largely Democratic. He called it the kind of audience
he was looking for. ''This is not a club for the rich and famous,''
he aid.
</P>
<P>
   On his lunchtime tour of the dining room and around the pool,
many members told Lazio they planned to vote for him or had not
made up their minds. If there was a consistent theme, it was
animosity toward Clinton as an interloper in New York politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope you beat the pants off her,'' Therese Bennett, 75, a
retired phone company employee, told the grinning Lazio. ''I can't
stand her. What the hell gives her the right to run in New York?''
</P>
<P>
   ''What are we going to do with that Hillary?'' asked another
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to work together,'' Lazio replied.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen O'Brien, a registered nurse from Brooklyn, who identified
herself as a delegate to the recent Democratic party convention
''but not for Hillary,'' engaged Lazio in a lengthy poolside
discussion on election issues, beginning with the ''salient
differences between yourself and the other candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Experience, ability to get the job done, be effective working
for New York in a bipartisan way. ... There are plenty of issues
but a lot of it is just being a legislator, knowing how to get the
job done,'' Lazio replied. He then itemized his views on taxes,
health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Though a Democrat, O'Brien said she disagreed with Mrs. Clinton
on some issues, and with ''the notion that she can just come into
New York'' to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that she doesn't necessarily want to be a senator
from New York, she wants to be a senator, and I think she sees it
as most expeditious within our state. If she thought it was most
expeditious in Illinois, she probably would have been the candidate
from there,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Mrs. Clinton's recent intercession to keep convicted
Israeli spy Jonathan Pollard from being moved to a tougher federal
lockup, Lazio said he thought the action proper and the decision
correct, but declined to voice a position on clemency for Pollard -
a sensitive issue in the Jewish community. Clinton has not taken a
position on clemency, either.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said only the president can decide on clemency, and if it
was denied by either President Clinton or a successor, ''they
should release to the public the underlying reasons and the facts
of why there was a denial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
