<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> jcnhr  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - While the economy boomed during the
1990s, incomes for Connecticut's poorest workers shrank more than
anywhere else in the country, according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut workers making the least amount of money saw their
incomes plummet 26 percent between 1988 and 1998, from an average
of $23,775 annually to $17,615, according to a report by New
Haven-based Connecticut Voices for Children and the Economic Policy
Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The $6,160 drop, adjusted for inflation, was the highest in the
nation. The second worst state was Rhode Island, where workers with
the lowest incomes saw their annual pay shrink by an average of
$3,781 over the past 10 years, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report also notes that the percentage of Connecticut workers
earning poverty-level wages increased in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the state's wealthiest workers made 18 percent
more money, a jump from an average $148,011 annual income to
$174,149.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ''The State of Working Connecticut 2000,'' uses data
from the state Department of Labor, the U.S. Census Bureau and
other sources to assess incomes, taxes, wages, unemployment, wealth
and poverty. It was released to coincide with the Labor Day
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   A national report also is being unveiled by the Economic Policy
Institute, a nonpartisan think tank that issues a state-by-state
labor report card every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Worsening poverty in Connecticut is largely due to the decline
of the manufacturing industry, said Shelley Geballe, president of
Voices for Children and author of the Connecticut report. Geballe
said she is alarmed to see poverty worsening in the nation's
richest state during a time of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Therrien, director of research for the state Department of
Labor, said he was not surprised by the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition to being the state with the highest per-capita
income... it's also been well publicized that we have five of the
poorest cities in the country. There is a gap there,'' Therrien
said.
</P>
<P>
   The labor department has initiatives underway to help
Connecticut workers find jobs and advance to higher-paying
positions, Therrien said.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Heerema, executive director of the Life Haven shelter for
homeless pregnant women in New Haven, said the rift between the
rich and poor has long been evident in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report documents what we've seen on a small scale at Life
Haven,'' Heerema said. ''Even with welfare reform, we've noticed
the declining wages among poor families, and that poverty-level
wages for workers have become more common.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
