<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Press Mideast Peace at UN  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will use this week's
millennial town meeting of the world's leaders as an opportunity to
restart the Middle East peace process while advocating a faster,
more effective United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   With virtually all the world's leaders at the table in New York
City for the U.N. Millennium Summit, the president will promote his
own diplomatic agenda, especially on the Middle East, according to
White House officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The president also will sketch plans on how the world body could
become quicker in dealing with international crises, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the summit, which runs Wednesday through Friday, Clinton
will seek to engage many of the 150 world leaders expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   On the schedule are face-to-face encounters with Russian
President Vladimir Putin, President Jiang Zemin of China, a number
of regional leaders, and the two key players at the deadlocked
Middle East peace talks -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The president's efforts to broker an Israeli-Palestinian peace
settlement during talks at Camp David in July ended in deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Through individual meetings and in speeches, Clinton will have
the chance to engage with a host of leaders, discussing issues
including the Middle East peace process, the spread of weapons of
mass destruction and the Balkans, one White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that Clinton might encounter -- on purpose
or by accident -- such leaders as Cuba's Fidel Castro or Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami. But there are no such sessions on the
president's public schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will deliver the summit's opening address, underscoring
the need for the United States to stay engaged around the world and
to find effective ways of addressing what one official called ''new
and very different kinds of security challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he is expected to address the situation in Sierra
Leone where a peace agreement has been signed but where conflict
has not ended, a White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is expected to discuss efforts to control the AIDS virus,
especially in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also is expected to endorse new tools and new resources
for the United Nations in an effort to sharpen its future role in
responding to world crises, preventing conflict and restoring
peace.
</P>
<P>
   In places such as Bosnia and Kosovo, ''the U.N, has done good
work but gotten off to a slow start,'' the White House official
said. He said Clinton will likely suggest ways to respond to needs
more quickly and effectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1707 </TRAILER>
