<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Sept. 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Agrees to Three Presidential Debates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush announced today that he has agreed to
three prime-time, presidential debates with rival Al Gore that could begin as
early as next week. The Republican presidential candidate said he is willing to
debate his Democratic rival Sept. 12 during a special prime-time edition of
NBC's ''Meet the Press;' Oct. 3 in Los Angeles on CNN's ''Larry King Live;'' and
Oct. 17 at Washington University in St. Louis. The proposal also includes two
vice presidential debates: Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C., and a later forum yet
to be decided, Bush said. Only one of the debates Bush has agreed to was
proposed by a special bipartisan commission, which had proposed three encounters
between Bush and Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Lieberman Kick Off Campaign Dash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Al Gore and Joe Lieberman today brought sandwiches --
cheesesteaks, of course -- for a night construction crew as the Democrats
stepped off on a manic 24-hour dash through five states designed to catch the
workingman's eye. ''Nobody's going to work harder for the American people,''
Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee, said in an interview on the running
mates' extraordinary Labor Day kickoff. With that image, superimposed on the
grueling schedule for this swing, Gore hoped to cramp Republican rival George W.
Bush's support -- so far unbudging in polls -- among working-class men,
particularly white men. Gore told The Associated Press his goal was to ''honor
the families that work hard to pay the bills and make ends meet.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Workers Say Internet Is a Vital Tool
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For many Americans, Internet access is not just a workplace
distraction, but a key component of their jobs, a new report says. About 37
percent of all full-time workers -- or 38 million people -- now have Internet
access at their jobs, and they're using it primarily for work-related research
and e-mail, says the report by the Pew Internet &AMP; American Life Project. Lee
Rainie, director of the project, says polling of workers shows that about
two-thirds of those with access to the Web on the job go online at least once a
day. Nearly three-quarters of workers with access say the Internet has improved
their ability to do their jobs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Plans Mideast Peace Push at U.N.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will use this week's millennial town
meeting of the world's leaders as an opportunity to restart the Middle East
peace process while advocating a faster, more effective United Nations. With
virtually all the world's leaders at the table in New York City for the U.N.
Millennium Summit, the president will promote his own diplomatic agenda,
especially on the Middle East, according to White House officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity. The summit schedule, which runs Wednesday through
Friday, includes meetings with Russian President Vladimir Putin, President Jiang
Zemin of China, a number of regional leaders, and the two key players at the
deadlocked Middle East peace talks -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
California Earthquake Injures Dozens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- The heart of Northern California's wine country was
sharply jolted early today by an earthquake that smashed windows and glassware
and knocked out power to thousands. ''It was like someone was just holding the
house and shaking it violently,'' said Alison Saether, who said plaster fell
from the ceiling of her Napa home. ''We were so panicked we couldn't even
move.'' The quake hit at 1:36 a.m. and measured a magnitude 5.2. It was centered
about 6 miles northwest of Napa, near the small town of Yountville, according to
the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lebanon Holds Parliamentary Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Billionaire businessman Rafik Hariri and his allies
appeared to be handily defeating Lebanon's prime minister and his backers in
elections Sunday, according to early unofficial returns, putting Hariri on
course for a possible clash with the president. Hariri, a former prime minister
who tried to rebuild Lebanon following its devastating civil war, hopes to once
again lead the government of Lebanon, where political fortunes depend heavily on
the desires of neighboring Syria. Residents of the former Israeli-occupied zone
in the south voted for the first time in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Redskins, Davis Reach Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stephen Davis, the NFC's leading rusher last season,
reached an agreement with Washington on a contract the team said would make him
a ''life-long Redskin.'' Terms of the agreement, which was finalized one day
before the start of the regular season, were not disclosed. The Washington Post
reported in its Sunday editions that the agreement was likely worth $90 million
over nine seasons, including a $6.5 million signing bonus. However, his salary
could be reduced if he does not meet certain performance standards, the
newspaper said.
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
