<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Delays Cardinals-Giants Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The NFL season opener between the
Arizona Cardinals and New York Giants was suspended for 23 minutes
by lightning early in the third quarter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were getting ready to punt after failing to pick up a
first down on the opening series of the second half when a bolt of
lightning flashed near the west end of Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The legs of Giants rookie receiver Ron Dixon seemed to turn to
jelly after the bolt, and referee Bill Carollo immediately waved
his arms in the air and sent the teams off the field into the
tunnels under the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants might have run faster, conscious of a lightning
strike that knocked five University of Albany police officers off
their feet during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't wasting any time,'' defensive end Michael Strahan
said after the Giants finished off a 21-16 win. ''After the
training camp incident, I wasn't going to be the poster child for
lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   The players warmed up briefly after returning to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say it was a little distracting because you usually
don't have to go back in and come back out,'' Giants coach Jim
Fassel said. ''It was the same for both teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants led 14-0 on two first-half touchdown runs by Tiki
Barber when play was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Joe Browne said there were two other ligthning
delays in NFL history. A game at Giants Stadium between the Jets
and Colts was delayed 32 minutes on Sept. 8, 1996, while a contest
in Kansas City between the Seattle Seahawks and Chiefs was delayed
54 minutes on Oct. 4, 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
