<HEADLINE> Iran Delays Review of Alleged Spies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- An Iranian appeals court is delaying for the
second time decisions on its review of the jail terms of 10 Jews
convicted of spying for Israel, state-run radio reported Sunday
night, quoting a senior judiciary official.
</P>
<P>
   The second review was apparently delayed for the same reason as
the first: the judges hadn't agreed on whether all the charges that
resulted in convictions constituted crimes, said Hossein Ali Amiri,
the judiciary chief of southern Fars province where the men were
tried.
</P>
<P>
   The main charges on which a lower court convicted the 10 were
espionage, cooperating with the Zionist regime and participation in
an illegal group. Defense lawyers had argued during the trial that
there is no definition of or punishment for espionage under Iranian
law.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 were convicted July 1 and sentenced to prison terms of
four to 13 years. Three others were acquitted. The case has
attracted international scrutiny, with critics questioning whether
the closed-door trial was fair; there was no jury and the judge
also acted as prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Amiri was reported as saying that the appeals court
would issue its verdicts by Aug. 21. Last month, he said the
verdicts were expected by Sept. 5. In Sunday's report, he said
there would be no decision by Tuesday, but he did not specify a new
date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
