<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Plan 27-Hour Campaign Dash  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman brought
sandwiches -- cheesesteaks, of course -- for a Sunday night
construction crew as the Democrats began a manic 27-hour dash
through five states designed to catch the working man's eye. ''You
are what this campaign is all about,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Running mate Lieberman pledged, ''No one will work harder for
the hard-working middle class families of America than Al Gore and
Joe Lieberman. Give us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopefuls, launching their extraordinary Labor
Day tour, carried in about 100 of Pat's ''King of Steaks''
specialties, then used Styrofoam slabs to cushion the plastic tubs
fashioned into dinner chairs. Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, only
pretended to nibble on the non-kosher meal.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye on the 22-page itinerary, dubbed ''Al and Joe's Hard
Day's Night Tour,'' Lieberman joked: ''I'm beginning to think vice
presidential candidates should have collective bargaining rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Union workers, mostly white men and some in hard hats, cheered
''Go Al, go!'' It was unclear how many were actually on duty this
holiday weekend or were part of a drummed-up union crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But with that image, superimposed on the grueling schedule for
this swing, Gore hoped to cramp Republican rival George W. Bush's
support -- so far unbudging in polls -- among working-class men,
particularly whites.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want a job done right on our economic policies take a
look at the blueprint,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe and I are offering a blueprint that will keep our budget
balanced, keep investing in new jobs ... keep interest rates low,
pass middle-class tax cuts, make sure that our prosperity enriches
not just the few but all of our families,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he ''will not accept the blueprint from the other side
that proposes to give away all of the (budget) surplus in a giant
tax cut for the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in an interview, Gore told The Associated Press his
goal was to ''honor the families that work hard to pay the bills
and make ends meet. ... They're the ones I want my presidency to be
about.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans want it to be about Gore's credibility, as
highlighted in a new television ad that began airing over the
weekend. It features Gore's 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple and his
1999 claim to have created the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was an alternative message Gore would like to
send voters, he replied: ''I'm for campaign finance reform and I am
for using our current prosperity to make sure that everybody
benefits from new advances in e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, Banani Scott, 29, an electrician working three
jobs to support two kids and the kind of guy Gore is after, was
unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''These guys are running around to show the people, 'We're down
with 'em,' then the next three or four years we won't see hide nor
hair of them. Nothing will change for me,'' said Scott, who added
he doesn't like Bush either.
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rain ruined plans to drop by a south Philadelphia
block party, so Gore and Lieberman settled for pizza at Doc's Union
Pub.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pizzo, 55, a teacher who was enjoying a few drinks, said
Gore on this sprint is ''demonstrating what he can do under strain,
demonstrating his physical prowess and mental acumen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the long day, Lieberman told reporters that any
explicit comparison to the pace of the GOP ticket will be up to the
American people and news media to draw.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going out to be with people who are actually working out
there and say that, while we know a lot of them have benefited from
the good economic times, we also understand a lot of them are
working very hard to make ends meet,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be with them and fighting for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett retorted: ''Twenty-four hours of
campaign promises cannot erase eight years of inaction on tax cuts
for working families, prescription drugs for our seniors, and a
'real' patients bill of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's communications director, Mark Fabiani, said it was
serendipity that Gore and Lieberman's ''work-athon'' would wind
through the key electoral battlegrounds of Pennsylvania, Michigan,
Florida, Kentucky and Illinois as Bush has had to defend the pace
of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we planned this, we didn't know what Bush was doing. It's
hard to believe he has such a light Labor Day schedule, but that's
his choice,'' Fabiani said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still made news Sunday, announcing he had agreed to three
debates with Gore. For the Labor Day holiday, which traditionally
kicks off the quadrennial fall campaign for the White House, Bush
planned one stop in Naperville, Ill., and another in Romeo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   After Philadelphia, the Democrats were headed to heavily
blue-collar Flint, Mich., to greet night shift workers at Hurley
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Next, was Tampa, Fla., for a 5 a.m. Monday breakfast with
firefighters and a pair of nostalgic sidetrips -- Gore to an
all-night diner like the one where his mother waitressed; Lieberman
to a bakery because his dad drove a bakery delivery truck.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the two were to split up, with Gore flying to the
Pittsburgh Labor Day parade and rally with AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney, then to Louisville, Ky., for an evening rally at the motor
speedway. Lieberman was breaking off for Detroit and Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Gore's campaign week is an economic address
Wednesday in Cleveland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 1950 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rebel Violence Kills 35  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A surge of rebel violence left 35 people
dead over the weekend following President Clinton's visit to
Colombia, including seven police officers slain by guerrillas --
some of whom were disguised as police.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest attack, leftist guerrillas from the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, sneaked up on a police station
Saturday in northern Colombia, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The assault took the small town of Tomarrazon by surprise, said
National Police operations director Gen. Tobias Duran.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas arrived in three trucks and a jeep, some dressed
in camouflage and others as police. Rebels shot to death the four
officers posted at the station and ambushed reinforcements as they
arrived, killing three more policemen, Duran added.
</P>
<P>
   Nine officers survived the attack, in which rebels also
destroyed the public telephone office in the town in Guajira State,
about 475 miles from the capital, Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   At least one FARC fighter died, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven other people were killed in heavy overnight clashes
that ended Saturday in western Colombia. Twelve of them were FARC
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Seven airmen died when their U.S.-built AC-46 gunship, which was
sent to support ground troops, slammed into an Andean peak. At the
mountaintop communications complex they were protecting, eight
soldiers died in fighting with guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels were unable to take the complex, which controls
cellular and other telephone links to much of western Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to the war-torn South American country was meant
to support President Andres Pastrana's fight against drug
traffickers and leftist rebels who protect drug crops. U.S. and
Colombian officials hope the $1.3 billion anti-narcotics aid
package will weaken the rebels and push them toward peace by
cutting into a major income source: taxes the FARC levies on the
cocaine trade.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics have said the aid, including helicopters and
troop training, is skewed toward the Colombian military, leaving
police forces increasingly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's neighbors have also expressed fears that U.S. aid
will increase the intensity of the war and cause fighting and drug
crop cultivation to spill over the border.
</P>
<P>
   A Brazilian newspaper Sunday quoted a FARC commander as saying
the rebel group will not allow fighting to spill over the border
and that it plans to send a document to the governments of
neighboring Venezuela, Brazil, Ecuador, Peru and Panama to this
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to calm our neighbors,'' FARC commander Ivan Rios was
quoted as saying in Folha de Sao Paulo. ''The territory of our
struggle is Colombia. It is our position that our popular struggle
should be carried out within our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The FARC has stepped up attacks on rural police stations during
the past two months, killing dozens of officers as well as
civilians. At least 231 police have died in the line of duty this
year.
</P>
<P>
   FARC attacks continue nationwide despite peace talks begun with
Pastrana in January 1999. The negotiations to end a 36-year
conflict are proceeding slowly and without a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Colombian navy intercepted a speedboat off its
Pacific coast on Sunday and seized three tons of cocaine, the navy
said. Two people were arrested in the operation, which turned up
more than a hundred packages stuffed with cocaine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
