<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Not Optimistic on Negotiations  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel will not make any moves in peace
negotiations until the Palestinians show flexibility, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak told his Cabinet Sunday, ahead of President
Clinton's latest effort to reconcile the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told his ministers that no breakthrough with the
Palestinians is imminent. Clinton will meet separately Tuesday with
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who will be in New York
for the U.N. Millennium summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prime minister emphasized that until now he didn't see any
signs of flexibility or openness from the Palestinian side that
could signify the possibility of the renewal of the negotiations,''
the official Cabinet minutes, released to the press, read.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on the stickiest issues blocking a final peace agreement
have faltered largely over the issue of Jerusalem. The three
leaders were unable to break the deadlock over the fate of the
disputed city at a U.S.-mediated summit in July.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to press the leaders to clinch a deal before his
term as U.S. president ends in January.
</P>
<P>
   At July's Camp David summit, Barak went further than any other
Israeli leader in offering the Palestinians sovereignty over parts
of east Jerusalem, which Israel captured in 1967. But Arafat
rejected the proposal, insisting he get full control of the sector
of the city he wants to make the capital of a future state.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat adviser Nabil Abourdeneh insisted Sunday that Israel
should make the concessions. The sides stand before a
''crossroads'' in the negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arafat will ask the American administration to put pressure on
Israel,'' Abourdeneh told reporters upon Arafat's return to Gaza
from a meeting of the Arab League in Cairo. ''The coming days will
be a test of Israeli seriousness and to know the American position
regarding the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel Two television reported Sunday that Barak would be
willing to surrender sovereignty over Muslim and Christian holy
sites in Jerusalem's Old City -- but only if the areas would not be
controlled by the Palestinians. Barak would also be willing to give
the Palestinians some control in the walled city's Muslim quarter,
the TV said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Army radio reported late Sunday that Israeli Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami left the country for secret talks in an
undisclosed location but did not provide details. Spokesmen for
Ben-Ami were not immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told Arab foreign ministers at the Arab League Sunday
that he would declare a Palestinian state but did not give an exact
date. His advisers have said he will not make a unilateral
announcement on Sept. 13 -- the deadline for a final peace agreement
-- but will put it off until November with the hope a treaty can be
reached by then.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going forward with great determination and willingness
toward ... establishing our independent Palestinian state and its
capital holy Jerusalem, the heart of Palestine, heart of Arabs and
heart of believers,'' Arafat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2002 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted Saudi Man Beheaded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- A Saudi man convicted of drug
trafficking was beheaded Sunday, the Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Madi Rbaihan Hamad al-Jamili was executed in the eastern
province of Hafer el-Baten for smuggling an unspecified quantity of
hashish into the kingdom, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   No other details were given.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's execution brings the number of people beheaded in the
kingdom this year to at least 92. At least 99 people were executed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Executions are carried out with a sword in a public square.
Saudi Arabia follows a strict interpretation of Islamic law, which
prescribes death sentences for murder, rape, drug trafficking and
armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations have criticized the executions,
saying the accused rarely receive a fair trial and that Islam calls
for limited use of execution as punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2003 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Delightful Dasher Wins AA Derby  </HEADLINE>
By PETE HERRERA
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUIDOSO DOWNS, N.M. (AP) -- A Delightful Dasher gave his owner
and trainer another scare and won another big race.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old gelding overcame a sluggish start with a huge
closing run to win Sunday's $225,000 All American Derby.
</P>
<P>
   A Delightful Dasher became only the fourth horse since 1974 to
win the All American Futurity as a 2-year-old and return the next
year to win the derby. The All American Futurity began in 1959 and
the derby was first run in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   This year's futurity will be run Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A Delightful Dasher, as he often does, spotted the competition
an early lead. He was bumped by two other horses a couple of jumps
away from the gate and the trio of Big On Charm, Significant Speed
and Exclusive Form dueled for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final 100 yards, A Delightful Dasher rushed into the
lead and hit the finish line a neck in front of Big On Charm, a
25-to-1 shot. Significant Speed was a neck behind Big On Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's trying to kill me. He's going to put me in a 6-foot
hole,'' said trainer John Bassett of My Delightful Dasher's
appetite for come-from-behind wins. ''This horse does things other
horses can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Gwendolyn Eaves of Midland, Texas, has gotten used to
seeing the gelding overcome trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just about gives me a heart attack, but that's what makes
him a great horse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Joe Badilla, who also rode A Delightful Dasher in last
year's All American Futurity, said the closer the finish line
loomed the better he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ''He broke decent, actually better than he usually does,''
Badilla said. ''But he makes me earn every dollar I've ever made on
him. The three horse (Big On Charm) put a little pressure on me,
but about 30 yards from the wire I sat on him really relaxed
because I knew he was going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was the eighth in 11 races over two years for A
Delightful Dasher. He covered the 440 yards in 21.477 seconds and
paid 44.609, $4.20 and $3 as the favorite. Big On Charm returned
$418.40 and $8.20 and Significant Speed paid $3 to show.
</P>
<P>
   A Delightful Dasher earned $123,172 to boost his career earnings
to $1,639,670.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2003 </TRAILER>
