<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stunt Pilot Flies Under Bridge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAUNAS, Lithuania (AP) -- With 200,000 spectators cheering him
on, a Lithuanian stunt pilot flew his plane upside down under a low
bridge in the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Jurgis Kairys, 48, turned over his Russian-made SU-26 and flew
under a bridge span Saturday with just 33 feet clearance between
the water and the concrete overhang.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers claimed it was the first time the extremely dangerous
stunt has been performed. Kairys said he didn't think he would do
it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not know if I would repeat the stunt even for a big
reward,'' Kairys said after flying along a river in the center of
the city at speeds approaching 180 mph. Kaunas is 60 miles west of
the capital, Vilnius.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 200,000 people watching from the Nemunas River bank
was Finnish Formula One racer Mika Hakkinen who came to see his
friend fly. ''This is fantastic and thrilling,'' Hakkinen said
after presenting Kairys with a Formula One racer helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Kairys flew under 10 low bridges along a winding river in
Vilnius last year. He has said he wanted to make flying under
bridges a tradition in the ex-Soviet republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
