<DOCNO> APW20000903.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Leader Works on POW Issue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- President Kim Dae-jung promised Sunday
to work for the return of hundreds of South Koreans believed held
in North Korea against their will, calling for more talks with the
North on the issue, a state news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have found, through various channels, that there are 700 to
800 such people. We will definitely resolve the issue,'' Kim said
in an interview with the nation's three major TV channels,
according to Yonhap news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the issue, we need more contacts (with North Korean
authorities) to bear fruits,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea says 454 South Koreans, mostly fishermen, were
abducted by the North. About 300 southern soldiers, captured during
the 1950-53 Korean War, are also believed to be held by the North.
Pyongyang has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea returned 63 former North Korean spies and guerrillas
on Saturday, many of whom spent decades in southern prisons.
Hundreds of thousands of North Koreans flocked the streets of
Pyongyang to welcome them back as heroes, northern media reported.
</P>
<P>
   The same day in Seoul, eight opposition legislators joined a
rally saying the governement should have demanded the return of
South Koreans held in the North.
</P>
<P>
   The repatriation of the former spies, freed after serving prison
terms ranging from 13 years to 45 years, is part of thawing
relations on the Korean peninsula following a June summit.
</P>
<P>
   After the summit, the first ever between the two states, the two
Koreas reopened a government dialogue and allowed brief reunions of
separated families. The Korean War ended in an armistice, not a
peace treaty, and the two states share the world's most heavily
armed border.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said North Korean leader Kim Jong Il would visit South Korea
in return for his June visit to Pyongyang, but the time of the
visit has not been fixed, Yonhap reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kim also said the North Korean leader agreed that U.S. troops
should stay in the South after the two Koreas reunify. Under a
mutual defense agreement, the Untied States, which fought on the
South Korean side during the Korean War, keeps 37,000 troops in the
South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2017 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0106 </DOCNO>
