<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kean Wins Rail Classic  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Laurel Kean completed a remarkable run
from driving range pro to LPGA Tour winner Sunday, shooting her
third straight 6-under-par 66 for a six-stroke victory in the State
Farm Rail Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Kean, 37, a regular on the tour from 1988 to 1998, left
competitive golf early last season and ended up giving lessons at a
Cleveland-area driving range.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lost faith in myself,'' Kean said. ''If I've got anybody to
thank, I should thank my family and a good friend of mine in
Cleveland who got me back motivated to play again. It was hard to
get that confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   She played her way into the tournament Monday, winning a
two-hole playoff with Caroline Gowan for the final spot in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I almost thought I would get in anyway as the fifth
alternate,'' Kean said. ''So I knew I had that cushion. I just
walked out there and felt comfortable. As far as after that, I
didn't really think about the total picture. I just took it day to
day.''
</P>
<P>
   She earned $135,000 for her first LPGA Tour title after making
only $6,600 in combined earnings on the LPGA Tour and Futures Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''No wonder my Visa bill is so high,'' Kean said.
</P>
<P>
   She also wrapped up a full exemption for 2001, but is not exempt
for the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kean chipped in from 30 feet for birdie on the par-4 10th hole,
and finished with seven birdies and a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to have a really good day, a good showing,'' she
said. ''If I didn't make birdie early on, I didn't want to rush it
and force anything.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I was going to be nervous. Players told me I would be,
but they said don't fight it. Just go with it. My mind was going
100 mph, so I tried just to let it go. I was six holes ahead of
myself, but when I got down to my shot, I took a deep breath and
thought slow.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's Mi Hyun Kim, the 1999 winner, shot a 68 to tie for
second with Dina Ammaccapane (69) at 204. Pat Hurst (67) was
another stroke back at 205.
</P>
<P>
   Australian star Karrie Webb, the tour leader with six victories
this year, closed with a 72 to finish 13 strokes back at 211.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2053 </TRAILER>
