<HEADLINE> Gore Opposes Anti-Union Measures  </HEADLINE>
By CRISTINE GONZALEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Reaching out to union members in a
battleground state, Al Gore is opposing two Oregon ballot measures
that would make it harder for organized labor to lobby and raise
money for political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this boils down to is that, once again, Al Gore is
showing that he is standing side-by-side with hard-working families
here and around the country,'' Gore spokesman David Chai said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opposition to the measures was to be announced at a Labor
Day rally in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon has voted for a Democrat the last three presidential
elections, but the state and its seven electoral votes are up for
grabs between Gore and his Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's position on the two Oregon measures isn't ''enough for
him to prevail as a presidential candidate,'' said political
scientist Bill Lunch of Oregon State University. ''But it is part
of a larger strategy that he's been using, and it seems to be
working -- in particular in the Pacific Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Measure 92 would prohibit unions from collecting money from
employees for political purposes through payroll deductions without
written permission. Measure 98 -- which prohibits the use of public
resources for political purposes -- would essentially ban unions
from lobbying the state Legislature, Lunch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
