<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressTad Nichols:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Tad Nichols, a photographer whose images of
nature, wildlife and geology graced the covers of National
Geographic and Arizona Highways, died Wednesday after complications
from a stroke. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols took up photography as a child and studied under Ansel
Adams and Brett Weston, said his granddaughter, Lisa DelViscovo.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from photography, Nichols also made nature films for Walt
Disney and documented scientific expeditions, including a 1944
Harvard University journey to Mexico's Paricutin volcano.
Edwin K.P. Wong:
</P>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- Edwin K.P. Wong, who had an early and
decades-long role in the growth of Hawaii's TV industry, died
Wednesday. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Wong was a retired vice president of KGMG-TV, a CBS affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The Honolulu-born Army veteran began his professional career in
1946 as an accountant with KGMB Radio. He later became KGMB-TV's
vice president and controller.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from KGMB in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Wong gave strong backing to TV production facilities,
particularly Hawaii Production Center, contributing to the growth
of the industry in the islands.
</P>
<P>
   Wong is survived by his wife, two sons, and a daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-03-00 2133 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000903.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turnovers Pile Up in Leaf's Return  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- It seemed just like old times for Ryan
Leaf. And that's not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf showed tenacity in coming back from two injuries in his
first real game for the San Diego Chargers in nearly 21 months, but
another rash of turnovers helped spoil the quarterback's return and
lead to a 9-6 win by the Oakland Raiders on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf was a mess afterward, both physically and on the stat
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   He needed seven or eight stitches to close a gash in his chin,
which came courtesy of a late hit by Raiders end Regan Upshaw in
the first quarter. He had to take IV fluids to combat cramping in
his legs, which forced him to the sideline for one play early in
the fourth quarter, accompanied by boos from Raiders fans. He said
he might have broken his non-throwing left hand; X-rays are planned
for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Just as painful to the Chargers were Leaf's three interceptions
and two fumbles, one of which he lost. That gives him 23 turnovers
in his short career, compared to just two touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could have done a lot more to help this team win today,''
said Leaf, who had a strong exhibition season to win back the
starting job he'd lost midway through his troubled rookie season of
1998. ''I've just got to take that this week and trudge forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf's first two interceptions were on overthrows, the first one
bouncing off Curtis Conway's hands to Marquez Pope. The next one
sailed past tight end Freddie Jones to nemesis Charles Woodson,
who's been picking on Leaf since his key end zone interception in
the Rose Bowl on Jan. 1, 1998, when Michigan beat Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf's fumble and his last interception really hurt. With the
Chargers at the Oakland 15 and trailing 2-0 late in the third
quarter, Leaf was hit by Lance Johnstone and the ball popped free.
Leaf reached for the ball, but was trapped under the pile and it
was out of his reach. It was scooped up by Upshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf came back to lead the Chargers on their only scoring drive,
an 80-yard march capped by Robert Chancey's 3-yard run. Leaf missed
one play on the drive with cramps.
</P>
<P>
   The second pick overall in the 1998 draft downplayed his
contribution on that drive.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the thing, it was just one drive,'' Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with the Chargers needing just inches to convert a
fourth down from their 29 with 1:25 to play, Leaf's pass to Jones
was picked off by linebacker William Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   As Leaf walked off the field, he looked back like he was
surveying a car wreck he'd just been in.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I could have gotten it over the top of the defender, we
probably could have had a 40- to 50- yard gain,'' Leaf said.
''We've got to hold our own, and that starts with me as the
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf completed just 17 of 39 passes for 180 yards. Chargers
receivers dropped several balls and slipped on the turf a few
times.
</P>
<P>
   While complimenting Leaf's toughness, coach Mike Riley said his
performance was erratic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like the game -- his play was tough at times. You just
can't win with turnovers,'' Riley said. ''Oakland did a nice job of
not turning the ball over in a very tough defensive game. We've got
to work to eliminate the turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf hadn't played in the regular season since Dec. 13, 1998,
when he mopped up in an embarrassing loss at Seattle. He said the
most difficult thing to adjust to was taking a beating and having
to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ''Honestly, it's going to feel good to be sore tomorrow, because
now I know I'm in there fighting with these guys,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
