<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Expects EU Sanctions Report  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WIELAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVIAN, France (AP) -- Austria's foreign minister said Sunday she
expects a European Union review panel to release a report this week
urging an end to sanctions imposed against her country for the
inclusion of a far-right party in its coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect a very objective, independent report'' that will urge
an early end to the sanctions, Foreign Minister Benita
Ferrero-Waldner told reporters during an EU foreign ministers
meeting in this lakeside resort.
</P>
<P>
   At weekend talks, Ferrero-Waldner lobbied her colleagues to bury
the mild diplomatic measures, which include boycotts of school
trips, cultural exchanges and military exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the EU has imposed sanctions against Austria
because the far-right Freedom Party, which is seen as opposing a
multicultural Western Europe, is in the government coalition of
Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
   A special three-person panel was named July 12 to determine if
Austria's government respects ''common European values'' of
democracy and human rights, and whether the sanctions should remain
in place.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner's 14 EU counterparts remained tightlipped. The
report will be sent to President Jacques Chirac of France, whose
country holds the EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must be patient and see what it says,'' said French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
   Austria has set a mid-October deadline to end the measures or it
may stage a referendum in which Austrians will be asked what they
think of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it does not come to a lifting of sanctions I would be very
disillusioned,'' Ferrero-Waldner told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions have polluted the atmosphere at EU meetings.
Opinion polls have shown a growing number of Austrians turning
against the EU.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions have also raised the possibility that an angry
Austria could veto the EU's eastward expansion plans, a course of
action favored by Joerg Haider, the ex-Freedom Party leader who
remains an influential force in the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
