<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction workers drill Gore, Lieberman over cheesesteaks  </HEADLINE>
By MARYCLAIRE DALE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - Over cheesesteaks from Pat's Steaks, six
Philadelphia construction workers peppered Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman on Sunday with policy questions that affect their
families - from college costs to health insurance limits to the
adoption of special needs children.
</P>
<P>
   ''We surprised them, because for a half-dozen construction
workers, we're educated,'' 35-year-old electrician Tom Betteridge
said.
</P>
<P>
   For white men in the same field of work, they also have diverse
family lives.
</P>
<P>
   Electrician John McClay, 55, of Gloucester County, N.J., has two
kids in college, one at the University of Pennsylvania. His wife
just lost her job in Paulsboro, N.J., after the Exxon-Mobil merger.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter Matt Haas, 45, and his wife, who live in
Franklinville, N.J., have adopted two children with special needs,
and have three of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Laborer Mike McLaughlin, 40, of Philadelphia, has a wife with
epilepsy that forced her to leave her job.
</P>
<P>
   Electrician Peter Misinkavitch, 38, of Jenkintown, has three
preschoolers and a teen. He is glad his wife could stay in the
hospital a second day following the birth of their younger
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''We asked about education, mental illness, health care,
Medicaid and jobs,'' Betteridge said.
</P>
<P>
   The group is working on a $160 million Hyatt Regency being built
at Penn's Landing in Philadelphia. Gore, the Democratic nominee for
president, and running mate Lieberman, a senator from Connecticut,
launched their frenetic, five-state Labor Day campaign swing at the
job site.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates talked in a small group with the selected workers
over dinner. Then they addressed a larger crowd of about 80 workers
and union leaders and a sprinkling of Democratic notables,
including Philadelphia Mayor John F. Street and Rep. Bob Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are what this campaign is all about. You are what America
is all about,'' Gore told the group of mostly white, middle-aged
men - a demographic that Republican nominee George W. Bush seems to
be winning, polls suggest.
</P>
<P>
   McClay said later that his union local nearly went bust during
the city's economic downturn in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 1990 and 1991, we had 60 percent of our people out of
work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, business is booming. Union electricians make about $33 an
hour after a five-year apprenticeship, a bit more than the other
construction trades, members said.
</P>
<P>
   McClay credits the turnaround in part to the 1992 election of
Gore and President Clinton, and to Ed Rendell's efforts as
Philadelphia's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But the union also took an activist approach to job creation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to McClay, the union decided to invest pension funds
in building projects like the one currently underway at Penn's
Landing. In exchange for the investment, they get a guarantee the
job will be done with union labor. They also hope the project has a
ripple effect on development in the area - offering them yet more
work in the future.
</P>
<P>
   After Gore's speech, Misinkavitch was asked what had appealed to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The working-class family stuff - lowering the deficit to
reduce taxes, the college deduction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had said that parents should be able to deduct the cost of
tuition if they help put their children through college.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got four kids - that would be a big plus,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-03-00 2157 </TRAILER>
