<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 6, Phillies 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Chan Ho Park won his fourth consecutive
start, allowing two hits over eight innings as the Los Angeles
Dodgers completed a three-game sweep of the Philadelphia Phillies
with a 6-1 victory Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' only hits off Park (15-8) were Scott Rolen's
two-out single in the first inning and Tomas Perez's leadoff single
in the eighth. The right-hander struck out six, tied a season high
with seven walks and induced three double-play grounders, while
matching his career high in victories.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who has won his last four starts, has not allowed more
than two earned runs in seven straight and is 5-1 with a 1.69 ERA
during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Park, still looking for his first complete game shutout in 136
career starts, came out after 131 pitches. He has left three games
this season after seven innings without allowing a run.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre and Shawn Green hit solo homers, and Gary
Sheffield had a pair of RBI singles for the Dodgers, whose pitching
staff limited the Phillies to one unearned run in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies have lost five straight. They've scored the fewest
runs in the majors, and until the ninth inning, had not scored
since the fourth inning Friday night, when Marlon Anderson came
home on Perez's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lieberthal scored in the ninth when Anderson's dribbler up
the first-base line was mishandled by reliever Terry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw retired Kevin Jordan with the bases loaded and two
outs for his 24th save in 31 chances, completing the four-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, whose eighth-inning solo homer beat the Phillies 2-1 in
the series opener, hit his 16th leading off the fifth for a 2-0
lead against Robert Person (7-5). Mark Grudzielanek had an RBI
single later that inning and Green led off the sixth with his 24th
homer for a 4-0 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added two more in the seventh against Cliff Politte
with Sheffield's RBI single and Green's run-scoring groundout. Park
ignited the rally with a leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   Person threw a strike on only one of his first 12 pitches. He
walked Tom Goodwin and Grudzielanek, then fell behind Sheffield 3-0
before giving up an RBI single to Sheffield on a 3-2 pitch with the
runners going.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has won 11 of 14 and a season-best six straight at
home, but remains seven games behind San Francisco in the NL West
and 6 1-2 games out of a wild card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Person was charged with four runs and five hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Phillies did not score an earned run against Dodgers
pitching for 28 consecutive innings. ... Person leads the Phillies'
staff with 77 walks. ... The three-game sweep was the Dodgers'
first against the Phillies since August 1997, at Veterans Stadium,
and enabled them to win the season series (5-4) for the fifth
straight year. ... Park (.216) and Person (.220) entered the game
3-4 in the NL in lowest opponents' batting average against. Only
Kevin Brown and Randy Johnson were better. ... Dodgers pitching
coach Claude Osteen held that same position in Philadelphia from
1982-88, when the Phillies produced three Cy Young winners -- Steve
Carlton, John Denny and reliever Steve Bedrosian. ... Lieberthal,
who last year became only the sixth catcher in major league history
with a .300 average and 30 home runs in a season, is hitting .280
with 15 homers this year. ... Dodgers SS Alex Cora returned to the
lineup after leaving Friday's game because of the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
