<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Sept. 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore: Bush's Debate Offer Too Narrow
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The presidential candidates squabbled over debate
schedules today as Republican George W. Bush announced he had accepted three
prime-time sessions, including one next week. Democrat Al Gore rejected the
plan, saying the formats proposed by Bush could limit the audience and amount of
face-to-face debate time. Bush proposed debating Gore as soon as next week, or
Sept. 12, during a special edition of NBC's ''Meet the Press;'' Oct. 3 in Los
Angeles on CNN's ''Larry King Live;'' and Oct. 17 at Washington University in
St. Louis. The proposal also includes two vice presidential debates: Oct. 11 in
Winston-Salem, N.C., and a later forum yet to be decided, Bush said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman Urged To Drop Senate Bid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The senator in charge of getting Democrats elected to the
Senate wants Sen. Joseph Lieberman to quit his re-election campaign and deny
Connecticut's governor the chance to give his seat to a Republican if Lieberman
wins the vice presidency. Connecticut Democrats nominated Lieberman at their
state convention July 14, three weeks before Democratic presidential candidate
Al Gore chose him as his running mate. Lieberman said today that replacing him
by committee now would cause ''a lot of chaos'' for the party. ''The U.S. Senate
seat is too important to be filled on the run,'' he said. As chairman of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., is
leading the party's drive to win the seats necessary to overcome the
Republicans' 54-46 advantage in the Senate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Democrats on 'Work-athon' Campaign Trail
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman brought sandwiches --
cheesesteaks, of course -- for a night construction crew as the Democrats began
a manic 27-hour dash today through five states designed to catch the working
man's eye. ''You are what this campaign is all about,'' Gore said. Running mate
Lieberman pledged, ''No one will work harder for the hard-working middle class
families of America than Al Gore and Joe Lieberman. Give us a chance.'' With an
eye on the 22-page itinerary, dubbed ''Al and Joe's Hard Day's Night Tour,''
Lieberman joked: ''I'm beginning to think vice presidential candidates should
have collective bargaining rights.'' Union workers, mostly white men and some in
hard hats, cheered ''Go Al, go!''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Negotiators Continue Tire Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- With Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. and union leaders remaining
tight-lipped about their ongoing contract negotiations today, it remains unclear
just how much the tire maker's recent high-profile problems have affected its
position at the bargaining table. A union spokesman denied that last month's
recall of 6.5 million Firestone tires and a government investigation into
accidents allegedly related to the tires have changed the nature of the contract
discussions, which have been ongoing since March. ''The negotiations started a
long time before any of these issues arose,'' said John Duray, spokesman for the
United Steelworkers of America.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Activists: Sanctions Hurt Iraq Citizens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- U.N. economic sanctions against Iraq are missing their
target, hurting not President Saddam Hussein but ordinary civilians, a group of
U.S. activists said Sunday at the end of a six-week experiment in living among
the Iraqi working class. Five members of the Chicago-based group, Voices in the
Wilderness, told a news conference at the Iraqi Trade Ministry that their stay
in a low-income district of the southern city of Basra had shown them that
sanctions crippled the ability of Iraqis to have safe water and food.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Damp Weather Helps Fire Fight
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Rain and even snow helped firefighters make major
progress to contain western wildfires today, although a blaze sparked by
lightning forced the evacuation of a national monument on a busy Labor Day
weekend. Four tour buses and hundreds of tourists were turned away today from
Devils Tower National Monument in northeastern Wyoming because a 1,550-acre fire
was burning about 2&AMP;frac12; miles away, officials said. The damp conditions
helped firefighters make considerable progress, said Neil Hitchcock of the
National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho. ''We may have turned the
corner on the fires in Montana and Idaho, but we aren't out of the woods yet,''
he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Open: Norman Beats Mirnyi
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Storms came and went, day turned to night, and after more
than eight hours of playing, waiting and playing again in brutal energy-sapping
humidity, Magnus Norman barely escaped the biggest exodus of top seeded men in
U.S. Open history. His red shirt soaked as if he'd been swimming in it, Norman
fell to his knees and pumped his fist over and over to the feverish fans after
the final point tonight in a 3-6, 4-6, 7-6 (5), 6-4, 7-6 (9) comeback against an
inspired but drained and cramping Max Mirnyi.
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
